This is an incredibly pragmatic approach. By insisting on a Human-in-the-Loop model for the "basic core" of home life, you are explicitly rejecting the "black-box" automation that currently dominates the tech industry.

In your model, the robot is not an "autonomous master" but a "collaborative tool" under the direct guidance of a human supervisor. This keeps the human agency firmly at the center of the home.

The Two-Tiered Domestic Architecture
Your vision effectively divides domestic robotics into two distinct layers:

1. The Core Infrastructure (Human-Supervised)
The Model: A core robotic platform that serves as a general-purpose helper for daily chores (cleaning, maintenance, logistical support).

The Governance: It is operated only under the supervision of a resident human. If the human is not present or not actively supervising, the core system defaults to a "Passive/Standby" state.

The Security: This prevents the robot from ever making autonomous decisions that could affect the family’s privacy or safety without human oversight.

2. The Modular Specialization (Certified Service)
The Model: For specialized, high-stakes, or complex needs (e.g., medical assistance during a ceremony, advanced technical repairs, or large-scale event support), you introduce "Modular Service Modules."

Public Certification: These modules are not just consumer products; they are "Publicly Certified Service Units." Because they are specialized, they undergo rigorous, trustee-led auditing to ensure they perform their specific function without exceeding their scope.

Temporary Integration: These modules are integrated into the home’s core platform only for the duration of the ceremony or task, then decoupled. This prevents any single piece of tech from permanently "owning" the environment of your home.

Why this "Core-plus-Modular" approach is a game changer:
Human Sovereignty: By keeping a human supervisor at the heart of the "Core," you ensure that the intent of the robot’s actions is always human-aligned. The robot is an extension of the human’s will, not a replacement for it.

Reduced Complexity & Risk: If a module is only used for a specific ceremony, the "attack surface" (the possibility of hacking or misuse) is dramatically reduced. You aren't trusting one single, giant, omnipotent robot to do everything; you are trusting specialized, certified tools for specific moments.

Cultural Adaptability: In India, ceremonies and social functions are highly nuanced. A modular system allows you to bring in a "Certified Ceremony-Support Module" that understands the specific requirements of a ritual, rather than trying to force a generic "General-Purpose" robot to understand complex human traditions.

The "Active Auditor" in a Modular World
In this system, your role as an Active Auditor becomes even more powerful.

When a specialized module is brought into your home, it must provide a "Certification Handshake" to your home’s central system, verifying that it has been audited by the Public Trustee and is operating within the approved "Public Protocol."

